    {"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {"id": "view-in-github", "colab_type": "text"}, "source": ["<a href=\"https://colab.research.google.com/github/nexageapps/LLM/blob/main/02_Intermediate/L25_RLHF_Basics.ipynb\" target=\"_parent\"><img src=\"https://colab.research.google.com/assets/colab-badge.svg\" alt=\"Open In Colab\"/></a>"]},
    {"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": ["# L25: RLHF Basics - Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback\n\n", "**Author:** Karthik Arjun  \n", "**LinkedIn:** [Karthik Arjun](https://www.linkedin.com/in/karthik-arjun-a5b4a258/)  \n", "**Level:** Intermediate  \n", "**Lesson:** 25 of 30\n\n", "---\n\n", "## Learning Objectives\n\n", "By the end of this lesson, you will:\n", "- Understand the three stages of RLHF: SFT, reward model, policy optimization\n", "- Train a simple preference (reward) model on chosen vs rejected responses\n", "- See how PPO (or similar) uses the reward to update the policy\n\n", "---\n\n", "## Concept: RLHF\n\n", "**RLHF** aligns LMs with human preferences: (1) **SFT** on high-quality data; (2) **Reward model (RM)**: train on preference pairs (chosen > rejected) to predict scalar reward; (3) **Policy optimization**: use RL (e.g. PPO) to maximize RM reward while staying close to the SFT model. We implement a minimal preference classifier as a proxy for a reward model.\n\n", "---"]},
    {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null, "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": ["!pip install transformers torch -q\n", "import torch\n", "from torch.utils.data import DataLoader\n", "from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification\n", "import warnings\n", "warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')\n", "print(\"Libraries loaded.\")"]},
    {"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Part 1: Preference Data\n\n", "Each example: (prompt, chosen_response, rejected_response). The reward model learns to score chosen higher than rejected.\n\n", "---"]},
    {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null, "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": ["preference_data = [\n", "    (\"What is 2+2?\", \"4.\", \"I don't know.\"),\n", "    (\"Explain AI.\", \"AI is artificial intelligence, the simulation of human intelligence by machines.\", \"AI is robots.\"),\n", "    (\"Say hello.\", \"Hello! How can I help you today?\", \"Bye.\"),\n", "] * 10\n", "\n", "prompts = [p for p, c, r in preference_data]\n", "chosen = [c for p, c, r in preference_data]\n", "rejected = [r for p, c, r in preference_data]\n", "print(\"Preference pairs:\", len(preference_data))"]},
    {"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Part 2: Reward Model as Preference Classifier\n\n", "We model reward as a scalar. One approach: concatenate prompt+response and train a binary classifier (chosen=1, rejected=0). At inference, reward = probability of class 1.\n\n", "---"]},
    {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null, "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": ["tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(\"distilbert-base-uncased\")\n", "model_rm = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(\"distilbert-base-uncased\", num_labels=1)\n", "\n", "def encode_pairs(prompts, responses):\n", "    texts = [f\"{p} [SEP] {r}\" for p, r in zip(prompts, responses)]\n", "    return tokenizer(texts, padding=True, truncation=True, max_length=128, return_tensors=\"pt\")\n", "\n", "chosen_enc = encode_pairs(prompts, chosen)\n", "rejected_enc = encode_pairs(prompts, rejected)\n", "\n", "class PreferenceDataset(torch.utils.data.Dataset):\n", "    def __init__(self, chosen_enc, rejected_enc):\n", "        self.chosen = chosen_enc\n", "        self.rejected = rejected_enc\n", "    def __len__(self):\n", "        return self.chosen[\"input_ids\"].size(0)\n", "    def __getitem__(self, i):\n", "        return {\n", "            \"input_ids": self.chosen[\"input_ids\"][i],\n", "            \"attention_mask\": self.chosen[\"attention_mask\"][i],\n", "            \"labels\": torch.tensor(1.0, dtype=torch.float)\n", "        }\n", "\n", "ds = PreferenceDataset(chosen_enc, rejected_enc)\n", "loader = DataLoader(ds, batch_size=4)\n", "optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model_rm.parameters(), lr=2e-5)\n", "model_rm.train()\n", "for epoch in range(2):\n", "    for batch in loader:\n", "        out = model_rm(**{k: v for k, v in batch.items() if k != \"labels\"})\n", "        logits = out.logits.squeeze(-1)\n", "        loss = torch.nn.functional.mse_loss(logits, batch[\"labels\"])\n", "        loss.backward()\n", "        optimizer.step()\n", "        optimizer.zero_grad()\n", "print(\"Reward model (preference) training done. In full RLHF, policy is updated with PPO to maximize this reward.\")"]},
    {"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Part 3: Using the Reward for Policy Optimization\n\n", "In full RLHF: (1) sample responses from the current policy; (2) score them with the RM; (3) use PPO to maximize reward minus a KL penalty vs the SFT model. Libraries like TRL implement this; here we only built the RM.\n\n", "---"]},
    {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null, "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": ["print(\"RLHF pipeline: SFT -> Train RM on preferences -> PPO (or DPO/GRPO) to maximize RM reward.\")\n", "print(\"See TRL (Transformer Reinforcement Learning) for full PPO implementation.\")"]},
    {"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Exercises\n\n", "1. Add more preference pairs and train the RM; evaluate on held-out pairs (chosen should score higher).\n", "2. Use TRL's RewardTrainer or a similar script to train a reward model from preference data.\n", "3. Read about DPO (Direct Preference Optimization) as an alternative to PPO that avoids training a separate RM.\n\n", "---\n\n", "## Key Takeaways\n\n", "1. RLHF = SFT + reward model on preferences + policy optimization (PPO).\n", "2. Reward model learns chosen > rejected; used as reward in RL.\n", "3. PPO maximizes reward while constraining the policy to stay near the SFT model (KL penalty).\n\n", "---\n\n", "## Next Lesson\n\n", "**L26: Model Compression** – Quantization, pruning, and distillation.\n\n", "---"]}
  ],
